<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-617-665  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 617 665.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>InTech  Oct 1990 v37 n10 p42(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Wastewater integration ups productivity.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Dunn, Jeri; Rousso, Maurice.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The city of Phoenix implements a data communications networklinking a 37 million gallon per day Wastewater Treatment Plant anda 150 million gallon per day Wastewater Treatment Plant.andP;  Onlinedata gathering and storage, report generation, and historicaltrending can be done by staff at both locations using oneintegrated network.andP;  EMA Services was selected by the city toreview the proposed configuration and recommend any changesnecessary to increase the flexibility of sharing information.andP;  Thesystem consists of an IBM 9370 and a token ring network linking amicrocomputer network for water quality enforcement andmonitoring.andP;  The major components of the network integrationinclude the IBM 9370, two MicroVax 3600s, a PC LAN, and a JC-5000system.andP;  Advantages of the new system include quick availabilityof process and lab data and automatic generation of EPA reports.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   EMA Services (Services).andO;Topic:     ProductivityWaste ManagementNetworksGovernment RegulationPhoenix, Arizona.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Major components of network integration. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>